The clue I needed was the line number of the error :grin: 

Anyway, I found the problem ([updated demo](http://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/ddLrqa5o/)):

1. The demo was using dates in the table formatted as `Jan 01, 2015`, when it should be consistent with the format you want, specifically `DD-MM-YYYY`.
2. An older version of the datepicker and moment.js were being used with the latest version of jQuery.
3. The last version of Bootstrap isn't compatible with jQuery 3.0+; so the demo is using jQuery v2.2.4.
4. The date format for the datepicker was added to format the range value.

```js
$(function() {
  var $table = $('table')
    .tablesorter({
      theme: 'bootstrap',
      headerTemplate: '{content} {icon}',
      dateFormat: "ddmmyyyy",
      widgets: ['zebra', 'filter', 'uitheme'],
      widgetOptions: {
        filter_reset: '.reset',
        filter_cssFilter: ['', '', '', 'datepicker']
      }
    })
    .on('apply.daterangepicker', function() {
      $table.trigger('search');
    });
  $('.datepicker').daterangepicker({
    locale: {
      format: 'DD-MM-YYYY'
    },
    startDate: '20-09-2013',
    endDate: '20-01-2015'
  });
});
```

No problem @dauledk. Yes on the while loop. This is more or less what I'm doing:

```
def start_parent_stream():
    return db.child("<child to listen>").stream(stream_handler=stream_handler)


def listen_firebase_for_new_messages():
    parent_stream = start_parent_stream()
    while True:
        time.sleep(0.5)
        if not parent_stream.thread.is_alive():
            try:
                parent_stream.close()
            except Exception:
                client.captureException(tags={'handled_status': 'catched_and_logged'})
            parent_stream = start_parent_stream()
```

And to catch the exception I am basically maintaining a module that subclases several of the components of the core Pyrebase. In this case I modified the `stream` method to be able to receive a function under parameter `monitor` that wraps around the thread call, then I can pass the function when needed.  My actual code is somewhat different to also support this change: https://github.com/thisbejim/Pyrebase/pull/150. But the change should be something like this:

```
from pyrebase import pyrebase as pyrebase_internals


class CustomStream(pyrebase_internals.Stream):
    def __init__(self, url, stream_handler, build_headers, stream_id, monitor):
        self.monitor = monitor
        super().__init__(url, stream_handler, build_headers, stream_id)

    def start_stream(self):
        if self.monitor and callable(self.monitor):
            self.monitor(super().start_stream)
        else:
            super().start_stream()


class CustomDatabase(pyrebase_internals.Database):
    def stream(self, stream_handler, token=None, stream_id=None, monitor=None):
        request_ref = self.build_request_url(token)
        return CustomStream(request_ref, stream_handler, self.build_headers, stream_id, monitor)


class CustomFirebase(pyrebase_internals.Firebase):
    def database(self):
        return CustomDatabase(self.credentials, self.api_key, self.database_url, self.requests)


def custom_initialize_app(config):
    return CustomFirebase(config)

firebase = custom_initialize_app(FIREBASE_CONFIG)
```

And to initialize a stream:

```
from firebase import firebase

db = firebase.database()

def monitor_stream_of_events():
    try:
        return continue_stream()
    except Exception:
        client.captureException(tags={'handled_status': 'catched_and_logged'})

monitored_stream = db.child("<child_to_stream>").stream(stream_handler=stream_handler, monitor=monitor_stream_of_events)
```

The only purpose of this is to log exceptions, the actual restarting is done checking the threads. Hope you can follow up here :+1:

My data set is 8.9M and is all loaded from pickled lists generated by my CorpusTool, which is part of fBot (https://github.com/lesleslie/fBot - fBot lacks documentation but if you can install, run it, and  figure out what it does you'll realize that this is probably a good thing) but I will prob split it off because it is a standalone tool.  CorpusTool will scrape webpages for song lyrics, quotes, or movie scripts and generate pickled files of lists that can be loaded into the ListTrainer.  

See the file changes for pull request #916.  There are changes to mongodb.py that make it possible for me to use a dataset of this size which are not committed to the main branch (yet?).  Most notably changing distinct to aggregate and then increasing the size of the sort buffer.  Look at the file diffs.

With a dataset of this size, even with my changes, you should expect >2 mins for the query when using Levenstein distance.  If you only have 30k of data you should get almost an immediate response.  When trained with English corpora that comes with Chatterbot, and CorpusTrainer, I was getting really fast responses even with four logic adapters daisy-chained together - i.e.:

{
            'import_path': 'chatterbot.logic.BestMatch',  # Levenshtein distance by default
            'response_selection_method': 'chatterbot.response_selection.get_random_response',
        },
        {
            'import_path': 'chatterbot.logic.BestMatch',
            'statement_comparison_function': 'chatterbot.comparisons.synset_distance',
            'response_selection_method': 'chatterbot.response_selection.get_random_response',
        },
        {
           'import_path': 'chatterbot.logic.BestMatch',
           'statement_comparison_function': 'chatterbot.comparisons.sentiment_comparison',
           'response_selection_method': 'chatterbot.response_selection.get_random_response',
         },
        {
            'import_path': 'chatterbot.logic.LowConfidenceAdapter',
            'threshold': 0.24,
            'default_response': choice(st['low_responses']),
        }

(I don't use jaccard_similarity btw because even though it seems to be working sometimes it does generate a float error - at least on OSX).

Also, make sure you are using a version of ChatterBot >= 7.4.  If your training list is in bytes format too, i.e. b'my list string' your query performance will be much slower.  You shouldn't need to encode utf-8 to bytes if you are using Python 3.  (almost all of my recommendations are just from my experience or googling fyi).

-- les

